A numeric value that denotes a physical property of an object expressed as a proportion of a physical property with respect to a unit of time.The unit of measure for class word rate must be specified on an attribute-by-attribute basis. (Optional)
The numeric value that denotes the amount of PRECIPITATION deposited per unit time. The unit of measure is millimetres per hour.
A METEOROLOGIC-FEATURE that specifies the availability of natural illumination by type and time.
The specific value that represents the class of LIGHT.
The specific value that represents the phase of the moon for a specific LIGHT.
The character string representing a point in time that designates the time of day that marks the end of the period of effectiveness of the specified type of LIGHT.
The character string representing a point in time that designates the time of day that marks the beginning of the period of effectiveness of the specified type of LIGHT.
A METEOROLOGIC-FEATURE that specifies the distance at which an object illuminated by light in the visual spectrum can be detected.
The specific value that represents the class of obscurant that governs a particular VISIBILITY.
The one-dimensional linear distance representing the distance which can be surveyed using visual observation for a specific VISIBILITY.
A METEOROLOGIC-FEATURE that specifies the accumulation of frozen water on stationary or moving surfaces.
The specific value that represents the class of a particular ICING.
The specific value that represents the severity of a particular ICING.
JC3IEDM icing conditions of the environment.

A numeric value representing the quotient of two values that have the same unit of measurement, i.e., ratio has no units of measure. May be used to express a percentage. The allowable range must be specified on an attribute-by-attribute basis. (Optional)

The numeric quotient value that represents the velocity of light in a specific CLOUD-COVER as a fraction of the velocity of light in a vacuum, based on cloud height. This represents the inverse of the index of refraction. The value must be in the range from 0 to 1.
A METEOROLOGIC-FEATURE that specifies the velocity and directional characteristics of atmospheric movement.
The specific value that represents the class of WIND.
The specific value used to indicate the class of air stability.
The specific value used to indicate the class of the altitude for a specific set of reported wind data.
The specific value used to identify predicted wind values associated with nuclear fallout prediction for a specific Nuclear yield group.
The rotational measurement of the mean downwind direction at ground level in the hazard area towards which the cloud travels.
The numeric value that denotes the distance per unit time of a specific WIND. The unit of measure is kilometres per hour.
The rotational measurement clockwise between the line of true North and the direction from which a specific WIND originates.
A non-negative one-dimensional linear distance measure. This will be expressed in metres. (Optional)
The one-dimensional linear distance representing the elevation of the lowest cloud base for a specific CLOUD-COVER.
The one-dimensional linear distance representing the elevation of the highest cloud ceiling for a specific CLOUD-COVER.
A METEOROLOGIC-FEATURE that specifies the characteristics of clouds above Earth's surface.
The specific value that represents the prevailing class of a specific CLOUD-COVER.
The specific value that represents the average density of a specific CLOUD-COVER as fractional coverage.
The rotational measurement between two lines and/or planes diverging from a common point and/or line. This measurement will be expressed in units of degrees.
A METEOROLOGIC-FEATURE that specifies humidity, pressure, and temperature characteristics of Earth's atmosphere.
The specific value that represents the height of the inversion layer in the atmosphere. The stability class describes the degree of mixing of released material in the atmosphere.

The specific value that represents heat change with respect to the ground and 100 m in elevation in a certain area. Acts as an indication of vertical air movement between the ground and higher elevations.
The numeric value that denotes the ambient air in terms of force per unit area. The unit of measure is newtons per square metre.

The numeric quotient value that represents the proportion of water present in the air to the maximum amount of water (saturation point) possible at a given temperature and pressure. The value must be in the range from 0 to 1.
The numeric value that indicates the heat of the ambient air for a specific ATMOSPHERE.

A numeric value that denotes a physical property of an object expressed as a proportion of a physical property with respect to a unit of time.The unit of measure for class word rate must be specified on an attribute-by-attribute basis. (Optional)

A numeric value that denotes a measure of the physical property of an object. Class word quantity has a fixed unit of measure that must be specified on an attribute-by-attribute basis. Class word quantity is not to be used where class words angle, coordinate, count, dimension, and rate apply. (Optional)
A measure of degree of hotness or coldness in an object or in space. This will be expressed in degrees Celsius.
A non-negative one-dimensional linear distance measure. This will be expressed in metres. (Mandatory)
A METEOROLOGIC-FEATURE that specifies the type of particulate matter in the Earth's atmosphere and the rate of its descent onto the Earth's surface.
The specific value that represents the prevailing class of a specific PRECIPITATION.

A numeric value representing the quotient of two values that have the same unit of measurement, i.e., ratio has no units of measure. May be used to express a percentage. The allowable range must be specified on an attribute-by-attribute basis. (Optional)
